column10: Function questjson(k, v, elements, questname, portion, icon) : questjson = "{ ""key"": """ & k & """, " & IIf(IsEmpty(v), "", """value"": """ & v & """,") & " ""object_types"": [ " & Application.VLookup(elements, ActiveSheet.Range("$A$2:$B$9"), 2, False) & " ], ""description"": """ & questname & " quest " & portion & """, ""icon_url"": """ & icon & """ }," : End Function

column6: 0. Open file in Excel (or whatever can handle Excel-equivalent formulas).
column7: Note: The G1 formula has been verified to work correctly on Google Sheets. One should spot-check it anyway, just to be sure.

column6: 1. If G1 is text (starts with apostrophe), change it to a formula (starts with =). See #N/A.
column7: Note: The J1 function can be used as a shorter alternative in Excel; call with "=questjson(A1, B1, C1, D1, E1, F1)"

column6: 2a. Copy G1 to cells G9 through G(end); cell references: A1 becomes A9, $A$1 stays $A$1.
column7: Note: If more combinations of nwar are found, change the formula range (currently $A$2:$A$9) accordingly.

column6: 2b (alternative). Copy I1 to cells G9 through G(end) and implement J1 function.
column7: Note: If you add entries, make sure that you don't have cafe autocorrecting to café (amenity). In Excel: logo menu, Excel Options, Proofing, AutoCorrect Options, Replace text as you type.

column6: 3. Confirm a few lines of JSON are correct, especially the nwar object types expansions.
column7: Note: Don't forget to remove the comma at the end of the last JSON entry after copy/pasting!

column6: 4. Copy/paste resulting JSON text in cells to your favorite editor. Remove last comma.
